{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Catherine Gage | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | birth_date = 18 May 1815 | birth_place = [[County Down]], [[Northern Ireland]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1892|02|16|1815|05|18|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Rathlin Island]], [[County Antrim]], [[Northern Ireland]] | resting_place = [[Rathlin Island]] | residence = | nationality = | citizenship = | known_for = botanical and ornithological illustration | notable_works = illustrated ''Birds of Rathlin Island'' | parents = Rev. Robert Gage, Catherine Boyd | relatives = | signature = }}
'''Catherine Gage''' (18 May 1815 – 16 February 1892) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] [[botany|botanist]], botanical and [[Ornithology|ornithological]] illustrator.<ref name="DIUB Gage">{{cite web|last1=Newmann|first1=Kate|title=Catherine Gage (1815 - 1892): Artist|url=http://www.newulsterbiography.co.uk/index.php/home/viewPerson/519|website=Dictionary of Ulster Biography|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Praeger|first1=Robert Lloyd|title=Some Irish Naturalists: A Biographical Notebook|date=1949|publisher=Dundalgan Press|location=Dundalk|url=http://www.botanicgardens.ie/herb/books/inetok.htm|accessdate=20 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223224747/http://www.botanicgardens.ie/herb/books/inetok.htm#|archive-date=2015-02-23|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
==Life== [[File:Manor House, Rathlin Island (1) - geograph.org.uk - 818593.jpg|thumb|Gage's home, Manor House, Rathlin Island]]
Catherine Gage was born in [[County Down]] on 18 May 1815,<ref>{{cite web|title=Catherine Gage|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p39097.htm#i390969|website=The Peerage|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> the daughter of Rev. Robert Gage and Catherine Boyd.<ref name="DIUB Boyd">{{cite web|last1=Newmann|first1=Kate|title=Catherine Gage (1791 - 1852): Historian|url=http://www.newulsterbiography.co.uk/index.php/home/viewPerson/518|website=Dictionary of Ulster Biography|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> Gage lived her entire life in the family home, Manor House on [[Rathlin Island]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=McCurdy|first1=John|last2=McCurdy|first2=Jennifer|title=Island History|url=http://www.rathlin-island.co.uk/history.html|website=Rathlin Island|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> Gage died 16 February 1892 and was buried on Rathlin Island.<ref name=Lett>{{cite journal|last1=Lett|first1=Canon H.W.|title=Botanists of the North of Ireland|journal=The Irish Naturalist|date=1913|volume=22|issue=2|page=26}}</ref>
==Illustration work== Gage seems to have devoted a large portion of her life to illustrating a book by her brother Robert Gage on the birds of Rathlin Island that was never published.<ref name=Battersby /> The book was styled on that of [[John James Audubon]]'s ''[[The Birds of America]]''.<ref name=Battersby>{{cite news|last1=Battersby|first1=Eileen|title=Women artists a feature of Slane sale|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/women-artists-a-feature-of-slane-sale-1.658977|accessdate=20 May 2015|agency=The Irish Times|date=4 October 2010}}</ref> During the course of this work she produced over five hundred watercolours of birds.<ref name="DIUB Gage" /> She also illustrated local plants, creating a list for the [[Botanical Society of Scotland|Botanical Society of Edinburgh]], the abstract for which was published in the 1850 ''[[Journal of Natural History|Annals and Magazine of Natural History]]''.<ref name=Lett /> She also worked with her sister, [[Barbara Gage]], illustrating the local flora as well as the fauna.<ref name=Butler>{{cite book|last1=Butler|first1=Patricia|title=Irish Botanical Illustrators & Flower Painters|date=2000|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|location=Suffolk|isbn=9781851493579|page=68}}</ref>
When the folio of bird illustrations was auctioned in 2010, they were sold for €13,500.<ref>{{cite web|title=Slane Auction Brings Over One Million Euro|url=http://antiquesandartireland.com/2010/10/slane-auction-results/|website=Antiques and Art Ireland|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref>
