==See also== * [[Table of divisors]]
{{DEFAULTSORT:Prime factors}} [[Category:Prime numbers]] [[Category:Elementary number theory]] [[Category:Mathematics-related lists]] [[Category:Mathematical tables]]

'''Wideband material''' refers to material that can convey [[Microwave]] signals (light/sound) over a variety of [[wavelength]]s. These materials possess exemplary attenuation and dielectric constants, and are excellent [[dielectric]]s for [[semiconductor gate]]s. Examples of such material include [[gallium nitride]] (GaN) and [[silicon carbide]] (SiC). 

SiC has been used extensively in the creation of [[laser]]s for several years. However, it performs poorly (providing limited brightness) because it has an [[indirect band gap]]. GaN has a wide band gap (~3.4 eV), which usually results in high energies for structures which possess [[electron]]s in the [[conduction band]].

